468
00:32:13,673 --> 00:32:17,741
and that these measurements allow us
to determine the cosmological parameters,

469
00:32:17,741 --> 00:32:21,654
the parameters which describe 
how the universe is evolving

470
00:32:21,654 --> 00:32:24,397
and what its composition is.

471
00:32:24,397 --> 00:32:28,883
The data, for this ambitious goal, will be
produced by the Euclid satellite of ESA

472
00:32:28,883 --> 00:32:33,200
which, starting from 2020, will
measure, with exceptional quality,

473
00:32:33,200 --> 00:32:36,801
the shapes of billions of galaxies
to see statistically 

474
00:32:36,801 --> 00:32:40,950
how the images are distorted
by the whole of the cosmic structures

475
00:32:40,950 --> 00:32:46,033
over a field of view which corresponds
to a third of the whole sky.

476
00:32:46,033 --> 00:32:50,541
So for now the future
of cosmology depends

477
00:32:50,541 --> 00:32:54,351
on our ability to map 
the whole universe and not

478
00:32:54,351 --> 00:32:57,750
just some well targeted areas as we were 
able to make until now.

479
00:32:57,750 --> 00:33:01,418
This concludes this week of lectures

480
00:33:01,418 --> 00:33:04,160
and our MOOC of introduction
to astrophysics.

481
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:08,380
We have introduced a large variety
of topics and described physical concepts

482
00:33:08,380 --> 00:33:12,506
hiding behind astronomical
observations and their interpretations. 

483
00:33:12,506 --> 00:33:15,840
The goal has been to understand
the principles,  rather than

484
00:33:15,840 --> 00:33:18,231
the detailed mathematical 
developments.

485
00:33:18,231 --> 00:33:20,742
I hope this goal has been achieved.

486
00:33:20,742 --> 00:33:22,960
But I especially hope that you
took as much pleasure

487
00:33:22,960 --> 00:33:26,452
in following this course as
we had preparing it.
